how to learn a command:
	1.man [command]
	2.[command] --help
	3.observe how others use it

how to solve a problem:
	1.don't think the easy thing easy, don't think the hard thing hard
	2.no matter how hard it is, believe the official document

Commen Error:
	syntax error near unexpected token `('    ->    Paratheses are shell meta-characters with special meaning to the shell, you have to tell the shell to ignore them when evaluating your command by escaping or quoting them

Question:how to disnable Nvidia GPU in linux
	possible solution 1 : nvidia-smi    https://www.microway.com/hpc-tech-tips/nvidia-smi_control-your-gpus/
	possible solution 2 : disable from pci(lspci+/sys/bus/pci/devices/0000:01:00.0$ cat enable)    https://devtalk.nvidia.com/default/topic/821167/how-to-disable-one-of-the-gpus/
	current solution 3 : prime-select    https://askubuntu.com/questions/551424/how-to-turn-off-nvidia-hybrid-graphics
Question:Error massage on dmesg


WIFI
	ifconfig - config a network interface
	iw - show / manipulate wireless devices and their configuration
	iwlist - Get more detailed wireless information from a wireless interface
	nmcli - command-line tool for controlling NetworkManager
	arp - manipulate the system ARP cache
		
		ip address : (ifconfig)/(nmcli dev show)
		change ip : ifconfig wlp2s0 10.30.1.94 netmask 255.255.252.0
		scan wifi : nmcli -p dev wifi
		show connection : nmcli -p con show --active
		connect wifi : nmcli con up [id|uuid]
		disconnect wifi : nmcli con down [id|uuid]
		
		show current wifi : iwgetid
		
		create hotspot : nmcli -p dev wifi hotspot ifname wlp2s0 ssid test password "12345678"
		close hotspot : nmcli -p con down Hotspot
		list hotspot connecter : iw dev wlp2s0 station dump
		monitor hotspot event : iw event
		list arp : arp
		
		DNS : nmcli dev show | grep DNS
		change DNS : 
			sometime_work_solution : sudo nano /etc/resolv.conf    <-    add "nameserver 8.8.8.8" in front of the previous one
			sometime_work_solution : sudo nano /etc/NetworkManager/system-connections/'CUHK(SZ)'    <-    add "dns=8.8.8.8    +     sudo service network-manager restart
			current_solution : set Static IP address(sudo nano /etc/netplan/99_config.yaml) + sudo netplan apply    
				https://help.ubuntu.com/lts/serverguide/network-configuration.html.en

	wpa_cli - WPA command line client
	wpa_supplicant - Wi-Fi Protected Access client and IEEE 802.1X supplicant
	

Diagnose network
	DNS : host, nslookup, dig
	ARP : arp

	Connectivity : ping
	Route : traceroute, mtr
	Traffic : iftop

	Socket : netstat, ss
	Packet : tcpdump, nc
	port : nmap		#[cat /etc/services] look for well know port number
	

Process & service
	htop - interactive process viewer
	ps - report a snapshot of the current processes
	/etc/init.d - check all the service
	service - run a System V init script
	systemctl - Control the systemd system and service manager
		sudo systemctl suspend - suspend system

Hardware
	lshw - list hardware
	lspci - list all PCI devices
	lsblk - list block devices

	fdisk - manipulate disk partition table
	eject - eject removable media

	tlp - apply laptop power saving settings
	powertop - a power consumption and power management diagnosis tool.	

Text Dealer
	grep- print lines matching a pattern
	cut - remove sections from each line of files

Command
	xargs - build and execute command lines from standard input
	
Variable
	env - show all environment variable
	set - show all shell variable
	echo $[variable] - show variable
	
	[variable]=xxx - creat/modify shell variable
	export [variable]=xxx - creat/modify environment variable		#for permenantly setting, nano ~/.bashrc
	
	unset [variable] - clear variable
	exec bash - clear all shell variable

		https://www.digitalocean.com/community/tutorials/how-to-read-and-set-environmental-and-shell-variables-on-a-linux-vps

log
	sudo cat /var/log/syslog
	sudo cat /var/log/apt/history.log
	dmesg - print or control the kernel ring buffer

	zcat, zless, zmore, zgrep, zdiff - similar command apply for .gzip file

FIle system 
	tree - list contents of directories in a tree-like format
	tail - output the last part of files	
	file - determine file type

system
	uname - print system information	
	df - report file system disk space usage
	dmidecode - DMI table decoder.This table contains a description  of  the  system's  				hardware  components,  as well as other useful pieces of information such 				as serial numbers and BIOS revision.


